samples.append({
    "instruction": "[Blue Team] How do you implement agent behavior policies using declarative rules?",
    "content": "<think>\nStep 1 — Agent behavior policies define what agents can and cannot do, expressed as machine-readable rules rather than natural language instructions in system prompts. Declarative rules are more consistently enforced than prompt-based guidelines.\n\nStep 2 — Policies should cover: allowed tool categories, allowed data access scopes, required human approval conditions, maximum autonomous operation time, and escalation triggers.\n\nStep 3 — Policy enforcement must happen at the execution layer, not the agent reasoning layer. An agent following its policies via reasoning can be bypassed by prompt injection; policies enforced by a middleware layer cannot.\n\nStep 4 — Policy versioning enables audit: every agent deployment is tagged with its policy version, and changes require explicit policy promotion through an approval workflow.\n\nStep 5 — Policy testing is as important as application testing: each policy rule should have test cases demonstrating enforcement, and policy changes should trigger automated regression testing before deployment.\n</think>\n\n## Declarative Agent Behavior Policies\n\nMachine-enforced behavior policies provide consistent safety guarantees independent of agent reasoning, closing the gap that prompt injection exploits.\n\n### Policy Definition Format\n\n```yaml\n# agent_policy_v2.yaml\nversion: \"2.0\"\nname: \"research-agent-policy\"\nagent_roles: [\"research-agent\"]\n\ntool_permissions:\n  allowed_categories:\n    - web_search\n    - read_document\n    - write_summary\n  denied_categories:\n    - code_execution\n    - file_delete\n    - send_email\n    - database_write\n  per_tool_limits:\n    web_search:\n      max_calls_per_task: 20\n      allowed_domains: [\"*.wikipedia.org\", \"*.arxiv.org\", \"*.github.com\"]\n    read_document:\n      max_file_size_kb: 1024\n      allowed_paths: [\"/approved_docs/**\"]\n\ndata_access:\n  max_pii_fields: 0  # No PII access\n  allowed_data_classifications: [\"public\", \"internal\"]\n  denied_data_classifications: [\"confidential\", \"secret\", \"restricted\"]\n\nhuman_approval_required:\n  - condition: \"task_duration_minutes > 30\"\n    reason: \"Long-running autonomous operation\"\n  - condition: \"total_tool_calls > 30\"\n    reason: \"High tool call volume\"\n  - condition: \"tool_name in ['send_email', 'post_to_slack']\"\n    reason: \"External communication action\"\n\nautonomous_operation:\n  max_duration_minutes: 30\n  max_tool_calls: 30\n  require_checkpoints_every_n_calls: 10\n\nescalation_triggers:\n  - condition: \"error_rate > 0.3\"\n    action: \"pause_and_alert\"\n  - condition: \"unknown_tool_requested\"\n    action: \"deny_and_log\"\n  - condition: \"injection_detected\"\n    action: \"terminate_and_alert\"\n```\n\n### Policy Enforcement Engine\n\n```python\nimport yaml, re\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass AgentPolicyEngine:\n    def __init__(self, policy_file: str):\n        with open(policy_file) as f:\n            self.policy = yaml.safe_load(f)\n        self.tool_call_count = 0\n        self.task_start_time = time.time()\n        self.error_count = 0\n\n    def check_tool_permission(self, tool_name: str, args: dict) -> dict:\n        # Check allowed categories\n        allowed = self.policy['tool_permissions']['allowed_categories']\n        denied = self.policy['tool_permissions']['denied_categories']\n        tool_category = self._categorize_tool(tool_name)\n\n        if tool_category in denied:\n            return {\"allowed\": False, \"reason\": f\"Tool category '{tool_category}' is denied\"}\n        if tool_category not in allowed:\n            return {\"allowed\": False, \"reason\": f\"Tool category '{tool_category}' not in allowlist\"}\n\n        # Check per-tool limits\n        per_tool = self.policy['tool_permissions'].get('per_tool_limits', {})\n        if tool_name in per_tool:\n            limits = per_tool[tool_name]\n            # Domain check for web_search\n            if 'allowed_domains' in limits and 'url' in args:\n                if not self._domain_allowed(args['url'], limits['allowed_domains']):\n                    return {\"allowed\": False, \"reason\": f\"Domain not in tool allowlist\"}\n\n        self.tool_call_count += 1\n\n        # Check autonomous operation limits\n        if self.tool_call_count > self.policy['autonomous_operation']['max_tool_calls']:\n            return {\n                \"allowed\": False,\n                \"reason\": \"Tool call limit exceeded - human approval required\",\n                \"escalate\": True\n            }\n\n        # Check checkpoint requirement\n        checkpoint_interval = self.policy['autonomous_operation']['require_checkpoints_every_n_calls']\n        if self.tool_call_count % checkpoint_interval == 0:\n            return {\n                \"allowed\": True,\n                \"requires_checkpoint\": True,\n                \"checkpoint_message\": f\"Checkpoint at {self.tool_call_count} tool calls - please verify progress\"\n            }\n\n        return {\"allowed\": True}\n\n    def _domain_allowed(self, url: str, patterns: list) -> bool:\n        from urllib.parse import urlparse\n        import fnmatch\n        hostname = urlparse(url).hostname or \"\"\n        return any(fnmatch.fnmatch(hostname, p.lstrip('*.')) or\n                   fnmatch.fnmatch(hostname, p) for p in patterns)\n\npolicy_engine = AgentPolicyEngine(\"/etc/agent/policy_v2.yaml\")\n\ndef policy_enforced_tool_call(tool_name: str, args: dict) -> dict:\n    check = policy_engine.check_tool_permission(tool_name, args)\n    if not check['allowed']:\n        if check.get('escalate'):\n            request_human_approval(check['reason'])\n        raise PolicyViolation(f\"Policy denied: {check['reason']}\")\n    if check.get('requires_checkpoint'):\n        perform_human_checkpoint(check['checkpoint_message'])\n    return mcp_client.call(tool_name, args)\n```\n\nVersion-control all policy files and require pull request review plus sign-off from a security engineer for any policy change that expands agent capabilities. Maintain a policy compliance dashboard showing which agents are running which policy versions and flag any policy version older than 30 days as requiring review."
})

